'''Charles-Joseph Pigeon''' (29 March 1838 &ndash; 18 March 1915) was born in [[Le Mesnil-Lieubray]] in [[Normandy]] in [[France]].
He started as a salesman in [[Le Bon Marché]] in [[Paris]], where he became a close friend of [[Ernest Cognacq]], subsequently the founder of the [[Samaritaine]] department store.
Pigeon became a dealer in cycle lamps and other lamps. His invention and manufacture of the '''Pigeon lamp''', a non-exploding gasoline lamp, in 1884 (exhibited at the ''Exposition universelle de 1900''), made him famous and wealthy. [[File:Pigeon D22.jpg|thumb|Grave of Charles Pigeon in [[Montmartre]] ]] After his death he remains noted for his family grave in [[Montparnasse Cemetery]] in Paris, which he commissioned in 1905 to hold up to 18 family members. The main feature is a life-sized bronze sculpture<ref>by Caveau</ref> of Pigeon (notebook and pencil in hand) and his wife lying on a bed, overlooked by an angel, which had been illuminated by a lamp for many years by his custodians<ref>Philippe Jullian, ''Montmartre'', 1977, p.31</ref>.
