'''''Hacker's Delight''''' is a software algorithm book by Henry S. Warren, Jr. and published by [[Addison-Wesley Professional]]. The first edition was released in 2002,<ref name="Warren_2002">{{Cite book |title=Hacker's Delight |first=Henry S. |last=Warren Jr. |date=2002 |edition=1 |publisher=[[Addison Wesley]] |isbn=978-0-201-91465-8}}</ref> and the second in 2013.<ref name="Warren_2013">{{Cite book |title=Hacker's Delight |first=Henry S. |last=Warren Jr. |date=2013 |edition=2 |publisher=[[Addison Wesley]] - [[Pearson Education, Inc.]] |isbn=978-0-321-84268-8}}</ref>  It discusses a variety of programming [[algorithms]] for common tasks involving [[integer]] [[Data type|types]], often with the aim of performing the minimum number of operations or replacing slow operations by faster ones (e.g., converting a divide by a constant into a multiply by another constant that gives the same result).<ref name="Maxfield_2012">{{cite journal |title=Book Review: Engineer's Bookshelf - Hacker's Delight by Henry S. Warren, Jr. |author-first=Max |author-last=Maxfield |journal=[[EE Times]] |date=2012-04-05 |url=http://www.eetimes.com/author.asp?doc_id=1286016 |access-date=2017-04-02 |dead-url=no |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170402223009/http://www.eetimes.com/author.asp?doc_id=1286016 |archive-date=2017-04-02}}</ref>  The second edition has new chapters on [[cyclic redundancy code]] and other [[error correcting codes]]. It also had a new appendix containing graphs of discrete functions.

