{{for|inducers in molecular biology|Inducer}} [[File:Test_inducer.png|thumb|right|An inducer designed for testing in water tunnels]] An '''inducer''' is the [[Axis of rotation|axial]] inlet portion of a [[centrifugal pump]] rotor, the function of which is to raise the inlet [[pressure head|head]] by an amount sufficient to prevent significant [[cavitation]] in the following pump stage.<ref name=nasa_sp8052>{{cite book|title=NASA SP-8052 Liquid rocket engine turbopump inducers|publisher=NASA}}</ref> It is used in applications in which the inlet [[pressure]] of a pump is close to the [[vapor pressure]] of the pumped liquid. Inducers are frequently included in design of [[turbopump]]s for liquid propellant [[rocket engines]], although they are used in other applications which require high suction performance.<ref name=Japikse2001>{{cite web|last=Japikse|first=David|title=Overview of Industrial and Rocket Turbopump Inducer Design|url=http://caltechconf.library.caltech.edu/101/1/OV-Turbopump.pdf|publisher=Concepts NREC|accessdate=17 May 2014}}</ref> [[File:Inducer_tip_vortex_cavitation.png|thumb|right|An inducer operating in an experimental water tunnel. The tip vortex cavitation phenomenon can be clearly identified.]]
== Use in rocketry == In order to achieve high [[delta-v]], the structural mass of a [[launch vehicle]] should be as low as possible. Liquid fuel tanks can be constructed lighter if the pressure within those tanks is kept low. Typically, for pump-fed rocket engines, the propellant tank pressures (and masses) are 1/10 to 1/40 of those in a pressure-fed rocket.<ref name=sutton2001>{{cite book|last=Sutton|first=George P.|title=Rocket propulsion elements (7th ed.)|year=2001|publisher=John Wiley&Sons|pages=218, 363|url=http://web.mit.edu/e_peters/Public/Rockets/Rocket_Propulsion_Elements.pdf|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130102204553/http://web.mit.edu/e_peters/Public/Rockets/Rocket_Propulsion_Elements.pdf|dead-url=yes|archive-date=2013-01-02}}</ref> The structural weight constraint also makes the rotating speed of the [[turbopump]] rotor as high as possible. For example, the rotating speed of the oxygen turbopump of the Japanese [[LE-7]] rocket engine is 18300rpm.<ref name=sutton2001 /> These two factors above combine to make the pump impeller very susceptible to cavitation. If cavitation occurs in the impeller, the performance of the pump will be severely degraded and the pump itself may be damaged.
